      "## How Generative AI (GenAI) Works – A Deep‑Dive\n",
      "\n",
      "Generative AI refers to any machine‑learning system that can **create new content** (text, images, audio, code, etc.) rather than just classify or predict it.  In practice, the most widely used generative models for language are **autoregressive transformers** (GPT‑style), while image generation often relies on diffusion models or GANs.  This guide focuses on the dominant paradigm for text—autoregressive transformer language models—while pointing out the key ideas that carry over to other modalities.\n",
      "\n",
      "---\n",
      "\n",
      "### 1. High‑Level Overview\n",
      "\n",
      "| Step | What Happens | Why It Matters |\n",
      "|------|--------------|----------------|\n",
      "| **Data collection** | Gather billions of documents (web pages, books, code, etc.). | The model learns patterns only where it has seen data. |\n",
      "| **Tokenization** | Convert raw text into a sequence of discrete tokens (words, sub‑words, bytes). | Enables a fixed‑size vocabulary and efficient embedding lookup. |\n",
      "| **Embedding** | Map each token to a dense vector. | Provides a continuous representation that the model can operate on. |\n",
      "| **Transformer stack** | Feed embeddings through stacked self‑attention + feed‑forward layers. | Captures long‑range dependencies and complex patterns. |\n",
      "| **Training objective** | Minimize cross‑entropy of next‑token prediction (autoregressive LM). | Forces the model to learn the probability distribution of language. |\n",
      "| **Fine‑tuning / RLHF** | Adapt the pretrained weights to a specific task or user intent. | Improves performance and safety for downstream use. |\n",
      "| **Inference** | Generate tokens one by one using a decoding strategy (greedy, beam, nucleus, etc.). | Produces the final text output. |\n",
      "\n",
      "---\n",
      "\n",
      "### 2. Data Pipeline\n",
      "\n",
      "1. **Corpus Construction**  \n",
      "   *Web‑scraped data, books, Wikipedia, open‑source code, scientific papers, etc.*  \n",
      "   The larger and more diverse the corpus, the more “knowledge” the model can embed.\n",
      "\n",
      "2. **Cleaning & Filtering**  \n",
      "   *Remove spam, non‑text, duplicates, profanity, and other undesirable content.*  \n",
      "   Helps reduce bias and improve safety.\n",
      "\n",
      "3. **Tokenization**  \n",
      "   *Byte‑pair encoding (BPE), WordPiece, SentencePiece, or unigram language models.*  \n",
      "   *Example:*  \n",
      "   ```\n",
      "   \"ChatGPT is great!\" → [\"Chat\", \"G\", \"PT\", \" is\", \" great\", \"!\"]\n",
      "   ```\n",
      "\n",
      "4. **Vocabulary Construction**  \n",
      "   *Typically 30k–50k tokens for large LMs.*  \n",
      "   Each token gets a unique ID that is used for embedding lookup.\n",
      "\n",
      "---\n",
